{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"Silent-success detection (wall-clock timeout + verdict schema-shape + structured refusal-as-content) plus two proven output self-heal tweaks on rebar's already-strong structured.py ladder.\n\n## Why\nA class of failures never raises — a safety refusal returned AS the answer (pydantic-ai #5221), an empty/truncated result that looks complete (#5769, #3219), a silent hang (#4681) — so exception classification structurally can't see them; they need result validation. Separately, rebar's `structured.py` already implements almost the whole OSS self-heal ladder (native-where-available, tolerant parse, deterministic json-repair BEFORE reask, targeted error-fed reask, fast-fail on truncation/refusal, bounded `OUTPUT_RETRIES=2`) — it needs only two cheap, proven additions.\n\n## What\n- Runtime result-validation on every gate call: reuse the existing `check_stop_reason`; add a verdict **schema-shape** check (a parseable verdict object — NOT \"non-empty output\", since a clean review legitimately has zero findings). The per-request/tool timeout from story fd1d is the silent-hang backstop.\n- **Truncation-within-a-schema-valid-verdict:** a schema-shape check alone is insufficient — a truncated response can still deserialize into a valid-but-stripped verdict. So the check is CONJOINED with the finish-reason signal: a verdict that parses BUT whose `finish_reason`/`stop_reason` indicates `length`/`max_tokens` truncation (already surfaced by `check_stop_reason`) is treated as degraded (routed, not returned as PASS/BLOCK), even though it parsed. Schema-valid AND untruncated is the pass condition.\n- **Refusal-as-content protocol (concrete, distinct from `check_stop_reason`):** `check_stop_reason` already handles the SDK case where `stop_reason/finish_reason == \"refusal\"/\"content_filter\"` with EMPTY parts. The gap (#5221) is a refusal returned as NON-EMPTY content while the provider signals a filter out-of-band. Detection rule: flag refusal-as-content when the response carries non-empty text parts AND `provider_details`/`incomplete_details.reason == \"content_filter\"` (OpenAI Responses) OR the Anthropic `stop_reason` indicates refusal despite text — i.e. key on the STRUCTURED provider signal, never a regex over the answer text (which false-fires on tickets/diffs discussing safety). A detected refusal-as-content is routed through story 30ff's SHARED `LLMOutcome` construction (it produces an `LLMOutcome` with `resolution_class = CHANGE_INPUT` + a sanitized diagnostic via the same helper the exception path uses) — NOT an independent second routing path — so field naming, sanitization, and diagnostic structure are identical whether the disposition came from an exception or from result-validation. Surfaced via `coverage`, not returned as a PASS/BLOCK verdict. (Handoff interface: 30ff exposes the `LLMOutcome` constructor + sanitizer that 978d calls.)\n- Output self-heal in `src/rebar/llm/structured.py` (EXPLICIT deltas vs current code, both confirmed absent today): (1) `structured.py:154` currently calls `repair_json(cand, return_objects=True)` WITHOUT a `schema=` arg — add `schema=<model>` for schema-guided deterministic repair before any LLM reask. The pinned `json-repair` exposes `schema=` + `schema_repair_mode` (verified: `repair_json` params include `schema`), so the consumer interface is present; AC confirms the installed version accepts it; (2) `runner.py:490`'s reask currently sends `instructions + schema_hint + \"your previous reply could not be parsed ({exc})\"` but NOT the raw prior output — add a bounded snippet of the model's faulty prior reply (`str(result.output)`, truncated) so the model can diff its own mistake (the LangChain `RetryWithErrorOutputParser` / Instructor pattern). Neither is present today; these are genuine additions, not re-statements of existing layers.\n- **Schema coordination:** the verdict schema-shape check validates against the verdict schema as OWNED by story 2eca (which adds `resolution_class`/`diagnostic`). This story does NOT edit the verdict JSON schemas — it consumes them; if it lands before 2eca, it checks the pre-existing shape and 2eca's additive fields do not break it.\n\n## Scope\n- Runtime checks + the two `structured.py` tweaks.\n- NOT in scope: a second-interpreter \"fixer\" LLM (`structured.py` explicitly rejects it as an anti-pattern; keep that stance); verdict-schema edits (owned by story 2eca).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Refusal-as-content (via structured signal) and empty/truncated-looks-complete are detected and routed, not returned as a PASS/BLOCK verdict.\n- [ ] A verdict schema-shape check replaces any \"non-empty output\" heuristic; a zero-finding clean review still passes (explicit test).\n- [ ] `json_repair` is called with `schema=<model>`; the targeted reask includes the bounded faulty prior output.\n- [ ] No second-LLM fixer is introduced; no verdict-schema files are edited by this story.\n- [ ] RED silent-success cases flip GREEN; `make test`/`make lint`/`make typecheck` green.\n\nFiles: `src/rebar/llm/structured.py`, `src/rebar/llm/runner.py`, the gate verdict-finalization path (read-only on `src/rebar/schemas/*`)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783621110622237001,"uuid":"0a4bcbb0-b26f-43b9-ae8c-476f46b7372a"}